{{NCAATeamSeason |Mode=football |Year=2005 |Team= Richmond Spiders |Image= Richmond Spiders text logo.svg |ImageSize=200 |Conference= Atlantic 10 Conference |ShortConference= A-10 |TSNRank= 8<ref>[http://www.sportsnetwork.com/merge/tsnform.aspx?c=sportsnetwork&page=cfoot2/misc/2005_poll.htm Sports Network's Final 2005 FCS College Football Poll]</ref> |FCSCoachRank= |Record= 9â4 |ConfRecord= 7â1 |HeadCoach= [[Dave Clawson]] |HCYear= 2nd |OffCoach= |OCYear |DefCoach= [[Russ Huesman]] |DCYear= 2nd |OScheme= |DScheme= |StadiumArena= [[University of Richmond Stadium]] |Champion=Atlantic 10 Conference Championship |BowlTourney= |BowlTourneyResult= }} The '''2005 Richmond Spiders football team''' represented the [[University of Richmond]] in [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[Division I (NCAA)#Football Championship Subdivision|Division I-AA]] [[college football]] during the [[2005 NCAA Division I-AA football season|2005 season]]. Richmond competed as a member of the [[Atlantic 10 Conference]] (A-10) under second-year head football coach [[Dave Clawson]] and played its home games at [[University of Richmond Stadium]].
Richmond finished the regular season with an 8â3 overall record and 7â1 record in conference play, sharing the A-10 title with the [[University of New Hampshire]]. The Spiders were awarded an at-large berth in the [[2005 NCAA_Division I-AA football season#Postseason|I-AA playoffs]]. The Spiders defeated third-seeded [[Hampton University]] in the first round of the playoffs, but fell in the quartfinals to [[Furman University]]. The Spiders finished the season with a #8 national ranking according to The Sports Network's Division I-AA poll.<ref>{{cite web|title=Final Sports Network's 2005 FCS College Football Poll|url=http://www.sportsnetwork.com/merge/tsnform.aspx?c=sportsnetwork&page=cfoot2/misc/2005_poll.htm|work=|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5k4H77eJd|archivedate=2009-09-26|deadurl=no|accessdate=2009-09-19}}</ref>
